1
00:00:07,019 --> 00:00:09,940
[SPEAKER_05]: We have our last candidate now, Rebecca Greenspan.

2
00:00:10,481 --> 00:00:17,043
[SPEAKER_05]: She's on special leave from her role as Secretary-General of UNCTAD, the UN Trade and Development.

3
00:00:17,083 --> 00:00:21,585
[SPEAKER_05]: She's the first woman to head UNCTAD in its 60-year history.

4
00:00:22,146 --> 00:00:31,690
[SPEAKER_05]: Before that, she served as Under-Secretary-General of the United Nations Development Program, UNDP, Secretary-General of the Ibero-American Conference,

5
00:00:32,410 --> 00:00:37,694
[SPEAKER_05]: and Vice President of Costa Rica, and she is nominated by her country, Costa Rica.

6
00:00:38,054 --> 00:00:40,176
[SPEAKER_05]: Please join me in welcoming Rebecca Greenspan.

7
00:00:50,363 --> 00:00:51,364
[SPEAKER_05]: It's so good to see you.

8
00:00:51,524 --> 00:00:53,045
[SPEAKER_05]: Nice to see you.

9
00:00:53,065 --> 00:00:57,148
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

10
00:00:58,449 --> 00:00:59,270
[SPEAKER_05]: Last but not least,

11
00:01:00,055 --> 00:01:02,236
[SPEAKER_05]: You have five minutes to convince us.

12
00:01:02,396 --> 00:01:05,316
[SPEAKER_05]: What is your vision as UN Secretary General?

13
00:01:05,356 --> 00:01:07,197
[SPEAKER_05]: Why would you want the job and how will you do it?

14
00:01:07,457 --> 00:01:11,018
[SPEAKER_05]: And at four minutes, I'll give you a one minute warning.

15
00:01:11,438 --> 00:01:14,359
[GRYNSPAN]: Can I do this so I don't give you my back?

16
00:01:14,479 --> 00:01:15,539
[GRYNSPAN]: I can see all of you.

17
00:01:15,779 --> 00:01:17,319
[GRYNSPAN]: Is that okay with you?

18
00:01:17,499 --> 00:01:17,719
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

19
00:01:18,199 --> 00:01:18,460
[GRYNSPAN]: Okay.

20
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:22,300
[GRYNSPAN]: So why am I running?

21
00:01:22,781 --> 00:01:24,201
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

22
00:01:25,401 --> 00:01:28,002
[GRYNSPAN]: I have said that the UN

23
00:01:28,853 --> 00:01:32,596
[GRYNSPAN]: And the world today is in a difficult moment.

24
00:01:33,377 --> 00:01:40,463
[GRYNSPAN]: Conflicts are going up, as everybody has said, and they are on the peak since 1945.

25
00:01:41,104 --> 00:01:45,708
[GRYNSPAN]: Trust in the organization is going down, and time is running out.

26
00:01:46,969 --> 00:01:48,750
[GRYNSPAN]: And I believe in the UN Charter.

27
00:01:49,171 --> 00:01:51,733
[GRYNSPAN]: I believe in the principles of the UN Charter.

28
00:01:52,394 --> 00:01:52,914
[GRYNSPAN]: I have said,

29
00:01:54,709 --> 00:02:06,315
[GRYNSPAN]: the daughter of peace, of two refugees of the Second World War that were able to have a dignified life because they found peace and respect in Costa Rica.

30
00:02:07,436 --> 00:02:14,479
[GRYNSPAN]: And I know what war takes away from you and what peace makes possible.

31
00:02:14,980 --> 00:02:20,843
[GRYNSPAN]: And that's why I'm running, because this is a consequential moment

32
00:02:21,603 --> 00:02:29,445
[GRYNSPAN]: for the international system, for international law, for the UN, and I want to be part of the solution.

33
00:02:29,545 --> 00:02:35,367
[GRYNSPAN]: I want to be the leader of an organization that means so much for so many.

34
00:02:36,947 --> 00:02:43,649
[GRYNSPAN]: Now, I am defending the UN, but not necessarily I am defending the UN as it is.

35
00:02:44,906 --> 00:02:54,070
[GRYNSPAN]: The UN has to reform and has to be more agile, more flexible, more nimble in certain ways.

36
00:02:54,670 --> 00:02:57,971
[GRYNSPAN]: It has to learn how to partner with others.

37
00:02:59,152 --> 00:03:04,534
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, in the UN, we have this mentality that everything has to happen inside the UN.

38
00:03:07,173 --> 00:03:14,621
[GRYNSPAN]: not only countries have more capacities, but there are regional organizations today that did not exist in 1945.

39
00:03:16,823 --> 00:03:26,447
[GRYNSPAN]: And we need to allow new actors to take a center stage in challenges that the world is facing.

40
00:03:26,987 --> 00:03:31,028
[GRYNSPAN]: The private sector has more capacities today, civil society.

41
00:03:31,668 --> 00:03:44,473
[GRYNSPAN]: So it's not only to bring them to the UN, it's for the UN to go to them and be able to support what they do, the things that they can solve, also help us to solve them.

42
00:03:45,253 --> 00:03:55,882
[GRYNSPAN]: And we are too accustomed to compete all the time between us and with the external world to be alone in the centerpiece of everything.

43
00:03:56,703 --> 00:04:11,155
[GRYNSPAN]: And when I say that the UN has to change and I have used a phrase that has been misinterpreted because I have said the UN cannot do more with less because we cannot do that forever.

44
00:04:12,477 --> 00:04:14,841
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need to do less with less.

45
00:04:14,981 --> 00:04:20,089
[GRYNSPAN]: But let me correct that and say we have to be more strategic in what we do.

46
00:04:20,469 --> 00:04:24,916
[GRYNSPAN]: We cannot just add on with less resources all the time.

47
00:04:26,158 --> 00:04:28,041
[GRYNSPAN]: My second point is peace.

48
00:04:29,652 --> 00:04:38,514
[GRYNSPAN]: And there we have to, you know, I have going around when I step down from the ANTA job to dedicate myself to the campaign.

49
00:04:39,414 --> 00:04:42,195
[GRYNSPAN]: And people ask me the same question.

50
00:04:42,815 --> 00:04:44,675
[GRYNSPAN]: Where is the UN?

51
00:04:45,375 --> 00:04:49,576
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, in these scenarios of conflict around the world, they don't see us.

52
00:04:50,556 --> 00:04:54,917
[GRYNSPAN]: And it's true that preventive diplomacy is something that you don't see.

53
00:04:55,997 --> 00:04:58,818
[GRYNSPAN]: But it's also true that there are things happening

54
00:04:59,865 --> 00:05:06,856
[GRYNSPAN]: in the negotiations, where conflicts are being resolved, where agreements are being forged, and the UN is not there.

55
00:05:07,819 --> 00:05:12,182
[GRYNSPAN]: So my second point is that the UN has to be back at the table.

56
00:05:13,242 --> 00:05:17,745
[GRYNSPAN]: And for that, the office of the Secretary General has to change.

57
00:05:18,886 --> 00:05:25,130
[GRYNSPAN]: The office has to be structured to have the capacity to support the good offices of the Secretary General.

58
00:05:25,170 --> 00:05:32,895
[GRYNSPAN]: That is the one thing that is clear in the Charter as the task of the Secretary General.

59
00:05:33,715 --> 00:05:37,177
[GRYNSPAN]: And we have to reform ourselves to do that.

60
00:05:37,258 --> 00:05:39,819
[GRYNSPAN]: And I can expand on that if you want.

61
00:05:39,839 --> 00:05:40,580
[SPEAKER_05]: You have 30 seconds.

62
00:05:41,120 --> 00:05:44,122
[GRYNSPAN]: And third, we need to think about the future.

63
00:05:44,422 --> 00:05:46,944
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to cooperate for the future.

64
00:05:47,404 --> 00:05:50,326
[GRYNSPAN]: Young people are anxious about their jobs.

65
00:05:50,526 --> 00:05:52,687
[GRYNSPAN]: Women are anxious about their rights.

66
00:05:53,368 --> 00:05:56,250
[GRYNSPAN]: So let's have also positive agenda.

67
00:05:56,270 --> 00:05:59,472
[GRYNSPAN]: There are so many good things happening at the same time.

68
00:06:00,152 --> 00:06:07,537
[GRYNSPAN]: Let's be able to have, you know, a coalition for cooperation for the future that makes sense for everybody.

69
00:06:16,682 --> 00:06:20,504
[SPEAKER_05]: The toughest of times, some would say the toughest of times in the UN's 80 years.

70
00:06:21,385 --> 00:06:27,169
[SPEAKER_05]: What gives Rebecca Greenspan the skills, the experience to make sure the UN is there?

71
00:06:27,429 --> 00:06:29,110
[SPEAKER_05]: What do you have that others haven't had?

72
00:06:30,505 --> 00:06:34,209
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, first of all, I have done a lot of things in my life.

73
00:06:34,529 --> 00:06:36,211
[SPEAKER_05]: But this is a difficult challenge.

74
00:06:36,271 --> 00:06:38,994
[SPEAKER_05]: What have you done that makes you qualify for this job?

75
00:06:39,434 --> 00:06:42,678
[GRYNSPAN]: I know that for many people this is an impossible job.

76
00:06:42,998 --> 00:06:45,020
[GRYNSPAN]: It has been described that way.

77
00:06:45,060 --> 00:06:45,321
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

78
00:06:46,842 --> 00:06:49,664
[GRYNSPAN]: I have had to deal with very difficult situations.

79
00:06:49,764 --> 00:06:57,249
[GRYNSPAN]: When I started my career in Costa Rica, we were in the last decade of Latin America.

80
00:06:57,349 --> 00:07:02,252
[GRYNSPAN]: We had defaulted in our debt, and I was in the Ministry of Finance.

81
00:07:03,152 --> 00:07:10,698
[GRYNSPAN]: And I had to navigate that situation that was with huge constraints, with huge pressures on you.

82
00:07:11,619 --> 00:07:27,652
[GRYNSPAN]: And I have learned to live under pressure, to take decisions, to take tough decisions, and also to be able to have the team and be the team leader that is necessary for those situations.

83
00:07:28,172 --> 00:07:36,074
[GRYNSPAN]: So I believe I am experienced, I am confident, I am determined, and I am a good leader.

84
00:07:36,615 --> 00:07:40,736
[GRYNSPAN]: So I can be the secretary and the general at the same time.

85
00:07:41,176 --> 00:07:42,416
[SPEAKER_05]: More general than secretary?

86
00:07:42,616 --> 00:07:47,978
[SPEAKER_05]: That's what the survey of the Global South said, that's what they want, more general than secretary.

87
00:07:48,138 --> 00:07:53,980
[GRYNSPAN]: Yeah, but you know, there is part of being a secretary that will be very important also this time.

88
00:07:54,512 --> 00:07:54,752
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes?

89
00:07:55,252 --> 00:07:57,534
[GRYNSPAN]: That is your management skills.

90
00:07:58,314 --> 00:08:05,438
[GRYNSPAN]: If you are going to reform the organization, you have to drive management and not allow management to drive you.

91
00:08:05,738 --> 00:08:10,281
[SPEAKER_05]: But you might have to be a general, maybe even a field marshal to put the UN at the centre.

92
00:08:10,661 --> 00:08:12,302
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's get some commitments from you.

93
00:08:12,362 --> 00:08:13,422
[SPEAKER_05]: This is going to be on the record.

94
00:08:13,462 --> 00:08:15,023
[SPEAKER_05]: People are listening and taking notes.

95
00:08:15,723 --> 00:08:24,148
[SPEAKER_05]: The One for Eight Billion campaign and the UN Association of the UK as a founding partner has called on all candidates during this campaign to commit

96
00:08:24,498 --> 00:08:25,939
[SPEAKER_05]: publicly to five principles.

97
00:08:25,979 --> 00:08:26,540
[SPEAKER_05]: You may know them.

98
00:08:27,060 --> 00:08:36,148
[SPEAKER_05]: One, disclosing financial, publishing financial disclosures, engaging with civil society, participating in transparent

99
00:08:36,730 --> 00:08:39,412
[SPEAKER_05]: General Assembly and Security Council processes.

100
00:08:39,833 --> 00:08:41,874
[SPEAKER_05]: Remember, no one wants it behind closed doors.

101
00:08:42,435 --> 00:08:47,399
[SPEAKER_05]: Respecting Article 100 of the UN Charter, in other words, independence from member states.

102
00:08:47,819 --> 00:08:50,241
[SPEAKER_05]: Nobody wants one or two or three countries to dominate.

103
00:08:50,742 --> 00:08:54,105
[SPEAKER_05]: And avoiding conflicts of interest with any current UN roles.

104
00:08:54,785 --> 00:08:56,167
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you accept these principles?

105
00:08:56,507 --> 00:08:57,007
[GRYNSPAN]: Absolutely.

106
00:08:57,528 --> 00:08:59,609
[GRYNSPAN]: Yeah, I think that they make sense.

107
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:12,133
[GRYNSPAN]: If you want a secretary general that is able to bring back trust in the organization, it has to start with integrity and with accountability.

108
00:09:12,353 --> 00:09:14,873
[GRYNSPAN]: And I am absolutely willing to do that.

109
00:09:15,334 --> 00:09:16,714
[SPEAKER_05]: We're going to hold you to it.

110
00:09:17,394 --> 00:09:18,094
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's go to some of the...

111
00:09:18,114 --> 00:09:18,894
[SPEAKER_05]: I hope so.

112
00:09:19,595 --> 00:09:20,575
[SPEAKER_05]: Me and everybody.

113
00:09:20,615 --> 00:09:20,895
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

114
00:09:22,335 --> 00:09:23,636
[SPEAKER_05]: Everyone here tonight and many more.

115
00:09:24,216 --> 00:09:27,997
[SPEAKER_05]: First question from the audience, Anne Kaproff from the UN.

116
00:09:28,117 --> 00:09:29,297
[SPEAKER_05]: She's in the United States.

117
00:09:30,409 --> 00:09:39,271
[SPEAKER_05]: The UN was founded to maintain peace and security, yet critics argue it's, well, as you said, increasingly absent from critical peace efforts.

118
00:09:39,951 --> 00:09:47,413
[SPEAKER_05]: How would you restore the organization's relevance, good offices, and trusted role in conflict diplomacy?

119
00:09:48,113 --> 00:09:56,475
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, we've touched on that, but what we've heard from previous secretary generals when you say, well, the Security Council is gridlock, what can we do?

120
00:09:57,615 --> 00:10:00,196
[SPEAKER_05]: We only are as good as our member states.

121
00:10:01,177 --> 00:10:02,678
[SPEAKER_05]: What would you do differently?

122
00:10:02,718 --> 00:10:03,719
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you want to reform it?

123
00:10:03,759 --> 00:10:04,460
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you want to take it?

124
00:10:04,480 --> 00:10:05,741
[SPEAKER_05]: How do you want to approach this?

125
00:10:06,181 --> 00:10:12,427
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, I said and I repeat that the office of the Secretary General has to be restructured.

126
00:10:13,468 --> 00:10:18,893
[GRYNSPAN]: You cannot do mediation and prevention in a

127
00:10:19,515 --> 00:10:22,496
[GRYNSPAN]: pyramidal, bureaucratic structure.

128
00:10:23,076 --> 00:10:24,697
[GRYNSPAN]: Bureaucracies are very important.

129
00:10:24,717 --> 00:10:26,278
[GRYNSPAN]: I come from Costa Rica.

130
00:10:26,958 --> 00:10:29,699
[GRYNSPAN]: I supported the civil service of my country, yes?

131
00:10:30,880 --> 00:10:36,242
[GRYNSPAN]: But you cannot ask from a bureaucracy to deliver on things they are not.

132
00:10:37,443 --> 00:10:38,203
[GRYNSPAN]: about to do.

133
00:10:39,004 --> 00:10:46,809
[GRYNSPAN]: And to have flexibility, to be agile, is not part of a bureaucratic structure that is, at the same time, pyramidal.

134
00:10:47,270 --> 00:10:55,035
[GRYNSPAN]: And that's why, you know, when we were negotiating the Black Sea Initiative, five people worked with me.

135
00:10:55,075 --> 00:10:56,056
[GRYNSPAN]: This was in the Ukraine War.

136
00:10:56,196 --> 00:10:57,157
[GRYNSPAN]: That's for the grain.

137
00:10:57,237 --> 00:10:57,657
[GRYNSPAN]: Exactly.

138
00:10:57,697 --> 00:11:05,323
[GRYNSPAN]: When we opened up the Black Sea for Trade, that was so important to avoid a food insecurity crisis in the world.

139
00:11:06,247 --> 00:11:13,712
[GRYNSPAN]: And, you know, I had a very small team, five people that reported only to me, and I reported to the Secretary General.

140
00:11:14,052 --> 00:11:14,593
[GRYNSPAN]: And it worked.

141
00:11:15,053 --> 00:11:15,233
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

142
00:11:15,513 --> 00:11:19,696
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, everything that we wanted to do after that was stopped.

143
00:11:20,577 --> 00:11:28,742
[GRYNSPAN]: So you need a structure that will be flexible, that will be accountable to the Secretary General, and you need the best team ever.

144
00:11:28,842 --> 00:11:32,485
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, the Secretary General has to have really robust

145
00:11:32,985 --> 00:11:36,927
[GRYNSPAN]: and qualified people that are able to take this agenda forward.

146
00:11:37,187 --> 00:11:37,487
[GRYNSPAN]: Good.

147
00:11:37,867 --> 00:11:39,167
[SPEAKER_05]: A question from the audience now.

148
00:11:39,268 --> 00:11:46,510
[SPEAKER_05]: Aziel Goulandres, Secretary General of the World Federation of UN Associations from Switzerland.

149
00:11:46,810 --> 00:11:47,611
[SPEAKER_05]: Good, you're here.

150
00:11:48,051 --> 00:11:49,772
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for coming all the way from Switzerland.

151
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:50,612
[SPEAKER_05]: What's the name of this?

152
00:11:51,192 --> 00:11:52,013
[SPEAKER_05]: The City of Peace.

153
00:11:52,313 --> 00:11:53,153
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, your question.

154
00:11:54,410 --> 00:11:55,731
[SPEAKER_02]: My name is Aziel Goulandris.

155
00:11:55,891 --> 00:11:58,072
[SPEAKER_02]: I am with the World Federation of UN Associations.

156
00:11:58,132 --> 00:11:59,132
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for being here.

157
00:11:59,232 --> 00:12:02,354
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you to UNAUK for organizing this.

158
00:12:02,694 --> 00:12:06,816
[SPEAKER_02]: The United Nations often, very often, consults civil society.

159
00:12:08,077 --> 00:12:13,079
[SPEAKER_02]: But consultation does not always mean that it translates into influence.

160
00:12:14,540 --> 00:12:18,642
[SPEAKER_02]: So if elected Secretary General, what mechanism

161
00:12:19,533 --> 00:12:35,103
[SPEAKER_02]: could we establish, could be established to ensure meaningful and geographically balanced civil society participation, including UN associations like this one, to ensure that their input affects decisions, not only discussions.

162
00:12:35,523 --> 00:12:36,103
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much.

163
00:12:36,764 --> 00:12:37,364
[SPEAKER_05]: A mechanism.

164
00:12:38,685 --> 00:12:47,150
[GRYNSPAN]: Yeah, I know that in the past there was a representation in the Office of the Secretary General of Civil Society that had

165
00:12:47,707 --> 00:12:54,771
[GRYNSPAN]: that role and that's something to be thought about and restored probably for that to happen.

166
00:12:55,251 --> 00:13:08,678
[GRYNSPAN]: But also let me say we need to hear civil society and partner with civil society not only because of money, it's not because of financial resources, it's also knowledge and capacities.

167
00:13:09,751 --> 00:13:14,413
[GRYNSPAN]: And that's why I meant that we need to partner much more.

168
00:13:14,513 --> 00:13:15,713
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to get a mechanism.

169
00:13:16,013 --> 00:13:19,575
[SPEAKER_05]: You're already talking about less with less, so you don't want to create new, but.

170
00:13:19,615 --> 00:13:22,996
[SPEAKER_05]: Less is refocusing, not downsizing.

171
00:13:23,036 --> 00:13:23,976
[GRYNSPAN]: Would you establish?

172
00:13:24,076 --> 00:13:29,458
[GRYNSPAN]: I already answered that there was a mechanism in the Office of the Secretary General that could be restored.

173
00:13:29,678 --> 00:13:31,139
[GRYNSPAN]: OK. That's what I said.

174
00:13:31,739 --> 00:13:34,280
[GRYNSPAN]: But I think that civil society also

175
00:13:35,066 --> 00:13:43,228
[GRYNSPAN]: I'm sorry to say, should not only think about how they influence the UN inside, but how they bring the UN outside.

176
00:13:43,268 --> 00:13:51,771
[GRYNSPAN]: They can help with that, not only on the one-sided way in which it has always been thought of.

177
00:13:52,211 --> 00:13:52,591
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

178
00:13:53,211 --> 00:13:56,472
[SPEAKER_05]: Another question from the floor, I understand.

179
00:13:56,852 --> 00:14:01,093
[SPEAKER_05]: Umar Diallo, Association des Familles des Martres de Senegal.

180
00:14:01,934 --> 00:14:02,494
[SPEAKER_05]: Vous êtes ici?

181
00:14:04,752 --> 00:14:05,053
[SPEAKER_05]: Omar?

182
00:14:05,735 --> 00:14:07,961
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, oh.

183
00:14:07,981 --> 00:14:08,403
[SPEAKER_05]: Senegal?

184
00:14:09,185 --> 00:14:09,887
[SPEAKER_05]: We moved yellow.

185
00:14:10,520 --> 00:14:18,962
[SPEAKER_04]: Hello, I'm Omou Diallo and I'm here representing Collective des Familles des Martyrs du Senegal entre 2021 et 2024.

186
00:14:19,703 --> 00:14:38,608
[SPEAKER_04]: My question is, how would you strengthen accountability and protection for victims of political repression in countries where state institutions are perceived as unwilling or unable to investigate abuses independently?

187
00:14:39,028 --> 00:14:39,428
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

188
00:14:41,750 --> 00:14:50,303
[SPEAKER_05]: How would you strengthen accountability and protection for victims of political repression in countries where state institutions are

189
00:14:50,902 --> 00:14:54,543
[SPEAKER_05]: perceived as unwilling or unable to investigate abuses independently?

190
00:14:55,103 --> 00:15:12,789
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, the main mechanism that we have is the human rights pillar and they have mechanisms to do that and it has to be put forward that that is happening and to ask for the intervention of the human rights commissioner.

191
00:15:13,550 --> 00:15:26,798
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that in the protection when civil rights have been abused, the main mechanism that the UN has is the human rights pillar.

192
00:15:29,468 --> 00:15:35,471
[GRYNSPAN]: and maybe thinking aloud now that we have the question, we haven't explained that around.

193
00:15:35,771 --> 00:15:40,534
[GRYNSPAN]: People don't know what are the mechanisms in the UN that we could use.

194
00:15:41,234 --> 00:15:48,938
[GRYNSPAN]: And that takes my attention to one problem that I haven't thought about, that maybe many people don't know.

195
00:15:49,630 --> 00:15:54,912
[GRYNSPAN]: What are the avenues or mechanisms that they can use to protect themselves with the UN?

196
00:15:55,533 --> 00:16:01,995
[GRYNSPAN]: And so that's probably a problem of communication because we speak in a way that nobody understands.

197
00:16:03,556 --> 00:16:14,861
[GRYNSPAN]: But also a problem of educating the population by the presence of the UN on the ground for them to know what are the mechanisms that can be enacted for that.

198
00:16:15,895 --> 00:16:26,371
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much for your question and it's an interesting reflection by you because certainly the survey which was done about the Global South, great dissatisfaction, disappointment with what the UN has done.

199
00:16:27,211 --> 00:16:28,152
[SPEAKER_05]: done or not done.

200
00:16:28,412 --> 00:16:34,095
[SPEAKER_05]: Most of all, a vast majority is saying it's too dominated by the powerful state.

201
00:16:34,195 --> 00:16:40,119
[SPEAKER_05]: So people are asking now for mechanisms which you say exist, but they're obviously not working well, not doing their job.

202
00:16:40,880 --> 00:16:42,921
[GRYNSPAN]: Another question... Well, they do their job in many parts.

203
00:16:43,201 --> 00:16:46,383
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, let's see, but there seems to be tonight an idea they've got to do a lot better.

204
00:16:46,864 --> 00:16:47,324
[SPEAKER_05]: Is that right?

205
00:16:48,325 --> 00:16:50,066
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

206
00:16:50,186 --> 00:16:53,188
[SPEAKER_05]: Ishan Shah from the UN Foundation is here.

207
00:16:55,009 --> 00:16:55,309
[SPEAKER_05]: Ishan?

208
00:16:56,658 --> 00:16:57,158
[SPEAKER_05]: Oh, thank you.

209
00:17:01,962 --> 00:17:02,642
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you so much.

210
00:17:02,682 --> 00:17:03,123
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

211
00:17:03,663 --> 00:17:07,526
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Ms. Greenspan, for being here today as well and for Dialogue Missile Society.

212
00:17:07,906 --> 00:17:15,651
[SPEAKER_00]: Through the World's Toughest Job Campaign by UN Foundation, thousands of young people helped write a job description for the next Secretary-General, which I have here.

213
00:17:16,452 --> 00:17:25,258
[SPEAKER_00]: They are asking to work with leaders to reform how the UN delivers for their communities as opposed to carry its consequences when expectations fall short.

214
00:17:25,718 --> 00:17:28,980
[SPEAKER_00]: You have spoken about the need for a more focused and effective UN.

215
00:17:29,401 --> 00:17:46,613
[SPEAKER_00]: So in your first year, what would you actually change in the Executive Office of the Secretary General, in the UN system, and the way priorities are set to ensure young people have real influence from the beginning, rather than being invited in only after priorities, budgets, agendas, and reforms have already been decided?

216
00:17:46,933 --> 00:17:47,293
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

217
00:17:48,154 --> 00:17:48,374
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

218
00:17:52,042 --> 00:18:11,708
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, I think that one of the things that the Secretary General has done is to create the office of the youth, precisely to preclude what he's saying about, you know, they have to live with the consequences of decisions that they were not part of.

219
00:18:12,972 --> 00:18:16,035
[GRYNSPAN]: But probably that mechanism needs strengthening.

220
00:18:16,516 --> 00:18:19,380
[GRYNSPAN]: And I have said in my vision statement that we will.

221
00:18:19,920 --> 00:18:24,906
[GRYNSPAN]: That one of the things that we are worried about is about the arms of the young people.

222
00:18:26,055 --> 00:18:36,620
[GRYNSPAN]: in front of a world that is changing a job space that they don't know how it will be, et cetera.

223
00:18:37,220 --> 00:18:51,947
[GRYNSPAN]: So it is a very important initiative that the Secretary General has taken, and I think that is something that should be strengthened and expanded for the future.

224
00:18:52,427 --> 00:18:53,788
[GRYNSPAN]: But I think that we have

225
00:18:54,438 --> 00:19:11,357
[GRYNSPAN]: a good seat there on which to work because the envoy of the youth has started to organize the youth around and it has done a very good job in trying to bring the youth really to the UN.

226
00:19:12,164 --> 00:19:21,089
[GRYNSPAN]: But the other part of this is how the UN will open up for the young to come to the UN to work with us.

227
00:19:21,469 --> 00:19:34,515
[GRYNSPAN]: And part of the mechanisms that we had before for underrepresented countries, for young people to come and reinvigorate the UN is now pretty small.

228
00:19:34,775 --> 00:19:37,217
[GRYNSPAN]: That is the entry point to the UN.

229
00:19:38,157 --> 00:19:49,781
[GRYNSPAN]: The entry point of the UN requires that you do exams for people to enter, young people to enter the UN at the basic level.

230
00:19:50,241 --> 00:19:51,821
[GRYNSPAN]: And that is a permanent job.

231
00:19:52,561 --> 00:19:55,342
[GRYNSPAN]: So they can build their career in the UN.

232
00:19:55,742 --> 00:20:04,305
[GRYNSPAN]: But because of the cuts and because of the financial restraint, those exams and those mechanisms have been weakened.

233
00:20:04,845 --> 00:20:05,306
[GRYNSPAN]: too much.

234
00:20:05,966 --> 00:20:10,091
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that that is one of the things that should also change.

235
00:20:10,171 --> 00:20:18,641
[GRYNSPAN]: Not only the representation at the political level, it's also the presence of staff of the UN to be able to be there.

236
00:20:19,061 --> 00:20:19,762
[GRYNSPAN]: And we need that.

237
00:20:20,843 --> 00:20:24,908
[GRYNSPAN]: We need the young people to come into the UN again.

238
00:20:25,881 --> 00:20:26,822
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much for your question.

239
00:20:26,842 --> 00:20:35,147
[SPEAKER_05]: I have to say we've received so many questions from young people saying they just don't feel there's a way to get them into the system and give them a real voice.

240
00:20:35,867 --> 00:20:40,430
[SPEAKER_05]: Another question, Jordan Ryan, former Assistant Secretary General of the UNDP.

241
00:20:40,730 --> 00:20:41,330
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe you know him.

242
00:20:42,051 --> 00:20:46,353
[SPEAKER_05]: The UN faces an acute crisis of funding, legitimacy and political confidence.

243
00:20:46,873 --> 00:20:52,397
[SPEAKER_05]: What would you do in your first year to protect the independence of the Secretary General?

244
00:20:53,137 --> 00:21:05,065
[SPEAKER_05]: reduce the organization's vulnerability to political blackmail by major contributors, no names mentioned, and prove that the UN can still act in the common interest.

245
00:21:06,186 --> 00:21:07,467
[SPEAKER_05]: You've talked about your office.

246
00:21:08,948 --> 00:21:14,972
[SPEAKER_05]: What would you do in your first year to solidify that independence against powerful voices?

247
00:21:15,612 --> 00:21:22,057
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, we have to fix the financial problem of the UN, yes?

248
00:21:22,675 --> 00:21:24,256
[GRYNSPAN]: And there are three things there.

249
00:21:24,596 --> 00:21:31,378
[GRYNSPAN]: First, we have to ask and demand as UN a stable panorama of finance.

250
00:21:31,698 --> 00:21:42,902
[GRYNSPAN]: No organization can reform and do all what we have to do if there is total uncertainty about the budget and the availability of resources in the organization.

251
00:21:43,663 --> 00:21:56,491
[GRYNSPAN]: Second, you will have to convince those that have the responsibility to finance the UN with assessed contributions, not only voluntary contributions, but assessed contributions that are obligations of the state.

252
00:21:57,371 --> 00:22:05,896
[GRYNSPAN]: Now, if you look at the panorama today, the US and China will represent 44% of the financing of the UN.

253
00:22:10,423 --> 00:22:13,485
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to ask ourselves, is that sustainable?

254
00:22:13,765 --> 00:22:18,488
[GRYNSPAN]: Actually, it's 44% because we put a cap on the maximum.

255
00:22:19,008 --> 00:22:26,233
[GRYNSPAN]: If not, the US will be paying 25% right now, and probably China will go in two years to be also 25%.

256
00:22:28,808 --> 00:22:31,870
[GRYNSPAN]: I think that this is a very difficult discussion.

257
00:22:32,030 --> 00:22:35,912
[GRYNSPAN]: And let me tell you that most of these experiments have avoided it.

258
00:22:36,292 --> 00:22:38,634
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, it goes to the heart of the problem now.

259
00:22:38,834 --> 00:22:39,514
[GRYNSPAN]: I think so.

260
00:22:39,714 --> 00:22:49,860
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that we have to put that on the table and find the collision of countries that are willing to open up at least that discussion.

261
00:22:50,540 --> 00:22:54,523
[GRYNSPAN]: But there is a third problem that we have, and it's the financial rules.

262
00:22:55,503 --> 00:23:09,619
[GRYNSPAN]: Because the financial rules that are right now imposed on the UN, they ask us to, and I don't want to enter into all the technicalities of the mechanism.

263
00:23:09,759 --> 00:23:10,239
[GRYNSPAN]: You've got 30 seconds.

264
00:23:10,520 --> 00:23:10,720
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes.

265
00:23:14,948 --> 00:23:17,770
[GRYNSPAN]: This is... You won't solve it tonight, but just one last...

266
00:23:17,790 --> 00:23:21,592
[GRYNSPAN]: I am not saying I'm solving it tonight, but this is a difficult thing to understand.

267
00:23:22,132 --> 00:23:29,197
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to give back money that we haven't received according to the financial rules that there are today.

268
00:23:29,657 --> 00:23:38,983
[GRYNSPAN]: And so what I am telling the countries is that they have to give us a moratorium at least of some of the financial rules for us to be able

269
00:23:39,778 --> 00:23:53,408
[GRYNSPAN]: to breathe in the next two to three years and solve the problem because we have to create the trust and the political will in the UN again also to solve the financial problem.

270
00:23:53,728 --> 00:23:56,350
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need these three things to happen.

271
00:23:58,332 --> 00:24:01,994
[SPEAKER_05]: It will certainly be the toughest of jobs, time consuming.

272
00:24:02,094 --> 00:24:04,616
[SPEAKER_05]: Please give us a reassurance before you leave this stage.

273
00:24:04,997 --> 00:24:07,699
[SPEAKER_05]: You'll find a way to relax so you don't collapse on the job.

274
00:24:08,639 --> 00:24:09,420
[GRYNSPAN]: I never collapse.

275
00:24:10,345 --> 00:24:11,065
[SPEAKER_05]: And do you relax?

276
00:24:11,906 --> 00:24:13,787
[GRYNSPAN]: I do relax with my family.

277
00:24:14,408 --> 00:24:15,308
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, tell us one thing.

278
00:24:15,328 --> 00:24:17,569
[GRYNSPAN]: My family, I love to be at home.

279
00:24:17,930 --> 00:24:20,031
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, I always on the run.

280
00:24:20,071 --> 00:24:23,433
[GRYNSPAN]: I am always in airports and airplanes.

281
00:24:23,773 --> 00:24:30,317
[GRYNSPAN]: When I go home, I just want to be home and talk to my granddaughter every day.

282
00:24:30,417 --> 00:24:31,418
[GRYNSPAN]: That helps a lot.

283
00:24:31,678 --> 00:24:34,420
[SPEAKER_05]: Rebecca Greenstein, thank you for sharing time with us.

284
00:24:38,368 --> 00:24:39,395
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you very much, Rebecca.

285
00:24:39,415 --> 00:24:40,261
[SPEAKER_01]: Really good to see you.

